The paper deals with the concept of locality sensitive hashing (LSH), which is a fundamental technique in computer science used for approximate nearest neighbor search. The paper provides a lower bound on the performance of LSH for the $\ell_1$ metric space, which is a well-studied problem in the field of data structures (cs.DS). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in the form of the parameter $\rho$, which is used to measure the performance of LSH. The paper uses geometric arguments and properties of metric spaces, which are common in computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves combinatorial arguments and probabilistic analysis, which are common in discrete mathematics (cs.DM) and machine learning (cs.LG).
